    <h1>Belgium immigrant population share: what official figures actually measure</h1>
    <p class="intro">Belgium has two widely cited figures for its immigrant population: 13.8% and 36.6%. Both are official. They measure different things, and conflating them is a common source of confusion.</p>
    <div class="lang-switch"><a href="/faq/belgique-population-immigree/">🌐 日本語版</a></div>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>The two official figures (Statbel 2026)</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Figure</th>
          <th>What it measures</th>
          <th>Source</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>13.8%</strong></td>
          <td>Non-Belgian nationals — people currently holding non-Belgian citizenship, registered in population registers (January 2026)</td>
          <td><a href="https://statbel.fgov.be" rel="noopener">Statbel 2026</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>36.6%</strong></td>
          <td>Population of foreign origin — persons born abroad <em>or</em> with at least one parent born abroad, regardless of current nationality (includes naturalised citizens)</td>
          <td><a href="https://statbel.fgov.be" rel="noopener">Statbel / census-based estimate</a></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why the gap is so large</h2>
    <p>Belgium has a high naturalisation rate. Many people born abroad or with foreign-born parents have acquired Belgian citizenship and are therefore <em>not</em> counted in the 13.8% figure. They are counted in the 36.6% figure.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The 13.8% figure counts current legal nationality — it excludes all naturalised citizens.</li>
      <li>The 36.6% figure counts ancestry — it includes naturalised citizens and their children if they were themselves born abroad or have a parent born abroad.</li>
      <li>Neither figure is wrong. They answer different questions.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Which figure to use?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>For legal/administrative comparisons (labour market access, voting rights, social entitlements): use <strong>13.8%</strong> (current nationality).</li>
      <li>For long-run demographic analysis or integration studies: use <strong>36.6%</strong> (foreign origin), but note it conflates first- and second-generation migrants and naturalised citizens — three very different groups.</li>
      <li>For cross-country comparisons with Denmark, Sweden, or Norway: their published figures are typically "foreign-born" (place of birth, regardless of nationality). Belgium's 13.8% (nationality) is <em>not</em> directly comparable to those figures.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Primary source</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Statbel (2026). <em>Population étrangère en Belgique — chiffres au 1er janvier 2026</em>. <a href="https://statbel.fgov.be" rel="noopener">statbel.fgov.be</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

